My mother's tea biscuits. My Nan's crybabies. My father's goulash. 

Food and family go hand in hand as far as I'm concerned.
I will always cling to those older ingredients because if we stop using them they will be gone for good.
Not trying to generalize, but people just aren't about baking and home cooking like they used to be.
Young people don't share great recipes anymore. They go out to nice restaurants or cook ramen at home.

My pantry has never been without @CrosbysMolasses. 

Just like my father and grandmothers before me.
I think the future of food is in rediscovering classic ingredients and using them in new ways.
It's sweet. It's savoury. It has a unique taste.
People see molasses as an ingredient in their grandma's recipe, but it's not just an old school Ingredient.
A lot of foodie friends are into using Sorghum or Agave syrup for baking. Why not molasses?
Have you guys watched Mind of a Chef on Neflix? So amazing.
